data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False."

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear failure message: "Expected: 3, Actual: 0"
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Not all returned users are active");

    // Checks the item exists (throws descriptive InvalidOperationException if not)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** over `Assert.IsTrue(x == y)` — gives you both values on failure
- **Add message strings** to `Assert.IsTrue` when you must use it, so failures are diagnosable
- **`users.Single()`** already throws if missing/duplicate — no need for a null check after it

**Other `CollectionAssert` options worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify collection contents
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList); // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);      // same items, same order
```

> **Note:** `CollectionAssert` works on `ICollection`, so you may need `.ToList()` if you have an `IEnumerable`.
